<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1881-07-06T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1881-07-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="411" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d411">
                    <head>No. 407.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Blaine</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Langston</persName></hi>.</head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1881-07-06"><hi rend="italic">July</hi> 6,
                            1881</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 156.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have received your No. 389 of the 18th
                        ultimo, touching the probable repeal of the law fixing a tax of one per
                        cent. for consular visas. The information contained in Mr. Laforestrie’s
                        private note to you of the 15th June is acceptable, and I trust that the
                        wise resolution of the Haytian Government to procure the abolition of this
                        obnoxious tax will be speedily accomplished.</p>
                    <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                    <closer><signed>JAMES G. BLAINE.</signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>